## Certificate Request Process

### Manual CSR Method (Current Implementation)

1. Generate Private Key and CSR:

```bash # Create SSL directory sudo mkdir -p /etc/nginx/ssl cd /etc/nginx/ssl

# Generate private key sudo openssl genrsa -out hostname.key 2048

# Create CSR configuration with SANs sudo tee hostname.cnf « 'EOF' [req] default_bits = 2048 prompt = no default_md = sha256 distinguished_name = dn req_extensions = v3_req

[dn] C=US ST=New York L=New York City O=LAB.LOCAL CN=hostname.lab.local

[v3_req] keyUsage = keyEncipherment, dataEncipherment extendedKeyUsage = serverAuth subjectAltName = @alt_names

[alt_names] DNS.1 = hostname.lab.local DNS.2 = service1.lab.local DNS.3 = service2.lab.local EOF

# Generate CSR sudo openssl req -new \

    key hostname.key \
    out hostname.csr \
    config hostname.cnf \
    extensions v3_req

```

2. Sign CSR with FreeIPA CA:

On mgmt.lab.local:

```bash # Get Kerberos ticket kinit admin

# Copy CSR from host scp user@hostname:/etc/nginx/ssl/hostname.csr /tmp/

# Sign certificate ipa cert-request /tmp/hostname.csr \

    -principal=HTTP/hostname.lab.local \
    -certificate-out=/tmp/hostname.crt

# Copy certificate back to host scp /tmp/hostname.crt user@hostname:/tmp/ ```

3. Install Certificate:

```bash # Move certificate to SSL directory sudo mv /tmp/hostname.crt /etc/nginx/ssl/

# Set permissions sudo chmod 600 /etc/nginx/ssl/hostname.key sudo chmod 644 /etc/nginx/ssl/hostname.crt

# Verify certificate SANs sudo openssl x509 -in /etc/nginx/ssl/hostname.crt -text -noout | grep -A1 “Subject Alternative Name” ```

## Nginx SSL Configuration

SSL Configuration Block:

```nginx # SSL protocols and ciphers ssl_protocols TLSv1.2 TLSv1.3; ssl_prefer_server_ciphers on; ssl_ciphers 'ECDHE-ECDSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-ECDSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:ECDHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384'; ssl_session_cache shared:SSL:10m; ssl_session_timeout 10m;

# HTTP to HTTPS redirect server {

  listen 80;
  server_name service.lab.local;
  return 301 https://$host$request_uri;

}

# HTTPS server block server {

  listen 443 ssl;
  server_name service.lab.local;

  ssl_certificate /etc/nginx/ssl/hostname.crt;
  ssl_certificate_key /etc/nginx/ssl/hostname.key;

  location / {
      proxy_pass http://backend:port;
      proxy_set_header Host $host;
      proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
      proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;
      proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-Proto $scheme;
  }

} ```

Mount SSL Directory in Docker:

```yaml services:

nginx:
  volumes:
    - /etc/nginx/ssl:/etc/nginx/ssl:ro

```

Important: Volume changes require container recreation:

```bash docker compose down docker compose up -d ```

## Client Configuration

To eliminate certificate warnings in browsers, install the FreeIPA CA certificate on client devices.

### Download CA Certificate

```bash curl -o ~/ipa-ca.crt http://mgmt.lab.local/ipa/config/ca.crt ```

### Linux (Arch/Ubuntu/Debian)

```bash # Copy to system trust store sudo cp ~/ipa-ca.crt /usr/local/share/ca-certificates/ipa-ca.crt

# Update CA certificates sudo update-ca-trust # OR on Debian/Ubuntu: sudo update-ca-certificates

# Restart browser to apply changes ```

### macOS

```bash # Install to system keychain sudo security add-trusted-cert -d -r trustRoot -k /Library/Keychains/System.keychain ~/ipa-ca.crt

# Restart browser to apply changes ```

### Windows

1. Download certificate from `http://mgmt.lab.local/ipa/config/ca.crt` 2. Double-click the certificate file 3. Click “Install Certificate” 4. Select “Local Machine” (requires administrator) 5. Select “Place all certificates in the following store” 6. Browse → “Trusted Root Certification Authorities” 7. Click OK → Next → Finish 8. Restart browser

### Firefox (Uses Own Certificate Store)

Option 1: Import Certificate 1. Settings → Privacy & Security → Certificates 2. View Certificates → Authorities tab 3. Import → Select ipa-ca.crt 4. Check “Trust this CA to identify websites” 5. Click OK

Option 2: Use System Certificates 1. Open `about:config` in Firefox 2. Search: `security.enterprise_roots.enabled` 3. Set to `true` 4. Restart Firefox

## Certificate Renewal

Certificates are valid for 2 years. Renewal process:

1. Generate new CSR using existing private key 2. Sign CSR with FreeIPA CA 3. Replace old certificate with new certificate 4. Restart nginx container

No downtime required if renewal is performed before expiration.

## Verification Commands

```bash # Check certificate expiration sudo openssl x509 -in /etc/nginx/ssl/hostname.crt -noout -dates

# Verify certificate SANs sudo openssl x509 -in /etc/nginx/ssl/hostname.crt -text -noout | grep -A1 “Subject Alternative Name”

# Test HTTPS connection curl -v https://service.lab.local

# Verify redirect from HTTP to HTTPS curl -I http://service.lab.local # Should show: 301 Moved Permanently, Location: https://...

# Check certificate from browser's perspective openssl s_client -connect service.lab.local:443 -servername service.lab.local ```

## Troubleshooting

### Browser Shows Certificate Warning

Cause: FreeIPA CA certificate not trusted on client device

Solution: Install FreeIPA CA certificate (see Client Configuration section)

### “Cannot load certificate” Error in Nginx

Cause: SSL directory not mounted in Docker container

Solution: 1. Verify volume mount in docker-compose.yml: `- /etc/nginx/ssl:/etc/nginx/ssl:ro` 2. Recreate container: `docker compose down && docker compose up -d` 3. Verify mount: `docker exec nginx ls -la /etc/nginx/ssl/`

### Certificate Request Stuck in certmonger

Cause: certmonger automation issues

Solution: Use manual CSR method instead (documented above)

### HTTP Not Redirecting to HTTPS

Cause: Missing HTTP redirect server block

Solution: Add redirect block to nginx.conf:

```nginx server {

  listen 80;
  server_name service.lab.local;
  return 301 https://$host$request_uri;

} ```

### “docker compose restart” Doesn't Apply Volume Changes

Cause: Restart reuses existing container configuration

Solution: Volume changes require container recreation:

```bash docker compose down docker compose up -d ```

## Backup and Recovery

### Backup

Certificate files backed up as part of nightly infrastructure backups.

Files: - `/etc/nginx/ssl/*.key` (private keys - keep secure!) - `/etc/nginx/ssl/*.crt` (certificates) - `/etc/nginx/ssl/*.csr` (certificate signing requests) - `/etc/nginx/ssl/ipa-ca.crt` (FreeIPA CA certificate)

### Recovery

1. Restore certificate files from backup to `/etc/nginx/ssl/` 2. Set correct permissions: ```bash

 sudo chmod 600 /etc/nginx/ssl/*.key
 sudo chmod 644 /etc/nginx/ssl/*.crt

``` 3. Restart nginx: `docker compose restart nginx` 4. Verify HTTPS works: `curl -I https://service.lab.local`

## Security Considerations

- Private keys (*.key) have 0600 permissions (owner read/write only) - Private keys never leave the host - Certificate files backed up securely - TLS 1.2 minimum (TLS 1.0/1.1 disabled) - Strong cipher suites only - Perfect Forward Secrecy enabled 
